      "comment_id" : 76290183,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "There are important cases where <i>bean</i> and <i>context</i> lifecycle are very different. As @HansWesterbeek noted a bean can be setup before the context it depends on is fully ready. In my situation a bean depended on JMS - it was fully constructed, so its <code>@PostConstruct</code> method was called, but the JMS infra-structure it indirectly depended on was not yet fully wired up (and being Spring everything just silently failed). On switching to <code>@EventListener(ApplicationReadyEvent.class)</code> everything worked (<code>ApplicationReadyEvent</code> is Spring Boot specific for vanilla Spring see Stefan&#39;s answer)."
